replyContent: Not really. The algorithm relies on detecting the app that's currently in the foreground, so as soon as you change to other app it'll drop the profile until the app applied through the profile is on the foreground again. There's nothing I can do about it without breaking the whole routine.

content: The app is functional and well laid-out, so I'll give it a five star rating, yet I'll say that I  do regret my decision to purchase the app. I didn't buy it because it was the best kernel management application, but to support the developer of this kernel. Since purchasing it, my Nexus 6 has received only one minor kernel update. While it is understandable that a developer has other commitments and that this may not be his main source of income, this developer has gained thousands of dollars in donations and application purchases, all provided with the aim of supporting him as he develops his kernel. Because of the developer's refusal to provide any timeline, I was ill-informed when purchasing this application as I'd assume many others were, and would appreciate if the developer were to either formally commit to future, frequent updates, or refund those who donated to support what was, at the time of their donation, an abandoned project. content: You cannot explicitly set the number when you modify the color control. You have to drag a progress bar, and it's not exact
replyContent: Yes its exact, any other values besides the ones in the slider are invalid to our hardware. It took us quite some time to research which values are valid and which ones are not because the hex values passed to the hardware need to be using certain bits due to some bit switching. I wouldn't be doing this way without an explanation.
